
NCAA Tournament Prediction Project Plan (NatStat API, EDA, and ML)
Executive Summary
We will build a Python-based project to predict NCAA tournament brackets using NatStat API data for women’s (WBB) and men’s (MBB) college basketball. First, we authenticate to NatStat’s v3 API (using the provided key) and download team, schedule, and boxscore data for both WBB and MBB. Next, we perform extensive EDA on each dataset (summary tables, distributions, trend charts)
. We then engineer features (team-level, matchup-level, and temporal features) and construct labels for game winners as well as tournament milestones (Sweet 16, Final 4, finals, champion). We split data by season for training/validation/testing. We try multiple supervised models (logistic regression, SVM, random forest, XGBoost/LightGBM, neural nets, and pairwise ranking approaches) with hyperparameter tuning. Evaluation metrics will include game-level accuracy and log-loss, and for higher rounds (Final 4, champion) we emphasize recall/precision (for example, champion recall is critical
). We also analyze feature importance (e.g. “Wins Above Bubble” was a top predictor in one study
), calibrate probabilities, and ensemble models. The code will be organized into three notebooks/files: 1_data_eda, 2_modeling, and 3_report_utils. Tables will summarize available API endpoints, model choices, and metric strategies. Finally, a project timeline (shown in Mermaid Gantt chart) lays out milestones from data acquisition through final reporting.

